  - STATE_UPDATE: {'solution_plan': 'Good! Now the fix is more robust. It checks if `[workspace]` exists before trying to delete it.\n\nBut wait, I just thought of something else. What if after we remove the `[workspace]` section, there are still issues with workspace inheritance? For example, what if some fuzz/Cargo.toml files have `authors = ["Automatically generated"]` instead of `authors = { workspace = true }`? That should be fine because it\'s a direct value, not workspace inheritance.\n\nActually, let me think about this more carefully. The root Cargo.toml has:\n- `workspace.package.version = "0.1.0"`\n- `workspace.package.authors = ["Linkerd Developers <cncf-linkerd-dev@lists.cncf.io>"]`\n- `workspace.package.license = "Apache-2.0"`\n- `workspace.package.edition = "2021"`\n- `workspace.package.publish = false`\n\nIf a fuzz/Cargo.toml has `authors = ["Automatically generated"]`, it will use that value instead of inheriting from the workspace. That\'s fine - it\'s an explicit override.\n\nThe real issue is with fields that use `{ workspace = true }`. They need to inherit from a workspace. After we remove the `[workspace]` section from fuzz/Cargo.toml, they will inherit from the parent workspace (root Cargo.toml), which should work.\n\nActually, I just realized there\'s one more thing to check. The fuzz/Cargo.toml files also have `tracing = { workspace = true }` in the dependencies. That should also work with parent workspace inheritance.\n\nI think this fix should work. Let me also check if we need to handle the Dockerfile. The Dockerfile is already correct with the digest format. No changes needed there.\n\n[HYBRID]: Strategy guided by General Principles from expert knowledge about Rust workspace inheritance issues, but implementation details are derived from code analysis of the specific fuzz/Cargo.toml file structures and the sed command needed to remove the problematic [workspace] sections.'}
